  1. Print the summary statistics of the data set and report how many discrete and continuous variables are in the data set.
# Enter your code here!
discrete_count <- 0
continuous_count <- 0

for (variable in names(mtcars)) {
  column <- mtcars[[variable]]
  
  if (all(column == floor(column))) {
    discrete_count<- discrete_count +1
  } else {
    continuous_count <- continuous_count+1
  }
}

print(paste("The dataset has", discrete_count, "discrete variables and", continuous_count, "continuous variables."))
## [1] "The dataset has 6 discrete variables and 5 continuous variables."
# Answer:
print(paste("The dataset has", discrete_count, "discrete variables and", continuous_count, "continuous variables."))
## [1] "The dataset has 6 discrete variables and 5 continuous variables."

  1. Create a crosstab that shows the number of observations belong to each cylinder and gear class combinations. The table should show how many observations given the car has 4 cylinders with 3 gears, 4 cylinders with 4 gears, etc. Report which combination is recorded in this data set and how many observations for this type of car.
# Enter your code here!
cyl_gear_table <- table(mtcars$cyl, mtcars$gear)

print("Crosstab of cylinder and gear class combinations:")
## [1] "Crosstab of cylinder and gear class combinations:"
print(cyl_gear_table)
##    
##      3  4  5
##   4  1  8  2
##   6  2  4  1
##   8 12  0  2
max_combination <- which(cyl_gear_table == max(cyl_gear_table), arr.ind = TRUE)
cyl_class <- rownames(cyl_gear_table)[max_combination[1]]
gear_class <- colnames(cyl_gear_table)[max_combination[2]]
max_count <- cyl_gear_table[max_combination]

print(paste("The combination with the highest number of observations is", cyl_class, "cylinders and", gear_class, "gears, with", max_count, "observations."))

Question 2

Use different visualization tools to summarize the data sets in this question.

  1. Using the PlantGrowth data set, visualize and compare the weight of the plant in the three separated group. Give labels to the title, x-axis, and y-axis on the graph. Write a paragraph to summarize your findings.
# Load the data set
data("PlantGrowth")

# Head of the data set
PlantGrowth
# Enter your code here!
boxplot(weight ~ group, data = PlantGrowth,
        main = "Comparison of Plant Weights by Group",
        xlab = "Group",
        ylab = "Weight of Plant",
        col = c("lightblue", "lightgreen", "lightpink"))

axis(1, at = 1:3, labels = c("ctrl", "trt1", "trt2"))

Result:

The control group ‘ctrl’ has a median plant weight of approximately 5.2. The weights in this group are fairly consistent, with the majority of values falling between 4.6 and 5.6, indicating a moderate spread. The treatment 1 group ‘trt1’ shows a lower median weight of around 4.6, suggesting that this treatment may have been less effective compared to the control group. Additionally, the variability in weights for ‘trt1’ is greater, with weights ranging from approximately 3.5 to 6. There is also an outlier in ‘trt1’, indicating that one plant had a significantly higher weight than the majority of plants in this group. The treatment 2 group ‘trt2’ shows the highest median weight, around 5.3, which suggests that this treatment had the most positive impact on plant growth. The data for ‘trt2’ is also more consistent compared to ‘trt1’, with weights ranging between 4.9 and 6.3. This consistency, along with the higher median, indicates that ‘trt2’ might be the most effective of the three groups in promoting plant growth.

=> Report a paragraph to summarize your findings from the plot!

The pairs plot of the ‘USArrests’ data set shows all possible scatter plots between the variables ‘Murder’, ‘Assault’, ‘UrbanPop’, and ‘Rape.’ The pairs plot provides an overview of potential correlations between the variables. From visual inspection, there seems to be a positive correlation between ‘Murder’ and ‘Assault’ rates, as well as between ‘Assault’ and ‘Rape’ rates. The ‘UrbanPop’ variable, which represents the percentage of the population living in urban areas, appears to be less strongly correlated with the other variables.The scatter plot between ‘Murder’ and ‘Assault’ rates indicates a strong positive relationship, meaning that states with higher murder rates tend to also have higher assault rates. This suggests that violent crime rates for these two types of offenses tend to increase together. The positive linear trend is clear in the scatter plot, and most data points cluster along an upward trend line, suggesting a strong linear association between these two variables.

=> Enter your answer here!

“Average Market Value per SqFt by Decade Built,” shows that properties built before 1850 have significantly higher average market values compared to properties from more recent decades.After the 1850s, the market value per square foot generally declines and remains relatively stable, with a few smaller peaks around the 1950s. However, there is a downward trend in average market value for properties built after the 1950s, with a notable drop for properties built in the 2000s. This suggests that newer constructions, while modern, may not hold the same market value as older properties, possibly due to location, quality, or other factors influencing buyer demand.”Histogram of Market Value per SqFt by Borough,” provides an overview of the distribution of market values across different boroughs. The histogram reveals that Manhattan (shown in teal) has a higher concentration of properties with high market values per square foot, indicating that this borough is consistently more expensive compared to others. Bronx and Staten Island have smaller and lower peaks, indicating fewer properties with lower market values compared to Manhattan and Brooklyn.
